.TH "DISPOSABLESTACK.DEFER" "3JS" "July 30, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
DisposableStack.defer \- DisposableStack.prototype.defer()
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]defer()\f[B]\f[R] method of \f[CR]DisposableStack\f[R]
instances takes a callback function to be called when the stack is
disposed.
.SH SYNTAX
.IP
.EX
defer(onDispose)
.EE
.SS Parameters
.TP
\f[B]onDispose\f[R]
A function that will be called when the stack is disposed.
The function receives no arguments.
.SS Return value
None (\f[CR]undefined\f[R]).
.SS Exceptions
.TP
\f[B]TypeError\f[R]
Thrown if \f[CR]onDispose\f[R] is not a function.
.TP
\f[B]ReferenceError\f[R]
Thrown if the stack is already disposed.
.SH DESCRIPTION
The primary purpose of \f[CR]defer()\f[R] is to register a cleanup
callback that\(cqs not specific to the disposal of a particular
resource.
If the callback is specific to a resource, you should use
\f[CR]use()\f[R] or \f[CR]adopt()\f[R] instead.
You can also use \f[CR]defer\f[R] when the resource is not claimed
within your code:
.IP
.EX
\f[B]function\f[R] consumeReader(reader) {
  using disposer = \f[B]new\f[R] DisposableStack();
  disposer.defer(() \f[B]=>\f[R] reader.releaseLock());
  \f[I]// Do something with reader\f[R]
}
.EE
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using defer()
This function sets a simple lock to prevent multiple async operations
from running at the same time.
The lock is released when the function completes.
.IP
.EX
\f[B]let\f[R] isLocked = \f[B]false\f[R];

\f[B]async\f[R] \f[B]function\f[R] requestWithLock(url, options) {
  \f[B]if\f[R] (isLocked) {
    \f[B]return\f[R] \f[B]undefined\f[R];
  }
  using disposer = \f[B]new\f[R] DisposableStack();
  isLocked = \f[B]true\f[R];
  disposer.defer(() \f[B]=>\f[R] (isLocked = \f[B]false\f[R]));
  \f[B]const\f[R] data = \f[B]await\f[R] fetch(url, options).then((res) \f[B]=>\f[R] res.json());
  \f[B]return\f[R] data;
}
.EE
